snippet.textDisplay:
Anyone want to guess what happened after the show? He rejected the deal, no surprises there, seems to happen more often than not.

The deal with Tej Lalvani saw Cadbury revert to the infamous wall twice to think about his options before finally accepting £75k for a 15% share. However, following a series of lengthy discussions and having met Lalvani several times after the episode was filmed, Cadbury has since decided to go it alone.

snippet.textDisplay:
Cadburys sold out to the Americans, now it tastes like all American chocolate. What a waste of a heritage.

Cadburys have always had a heritage of giving their profits to charity. That's why when times were tough, they had to sell out.

And it seems like the latest Cadbury is repeating his ancestor's mistakes. Investor had a death in the family so moved away - didn't see that as a way of taking the shares back.

I fear Cadburys are doomed to fail in this cutthroat world.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm sorry but just because you got the same surname and are related, doesn't mean you are as skilled or that your brand is as good or that your ancestors would even be fine with it just because you are distantly related. Notice how he relies on his connection and the name but not the quality. He just wants to make money off the backs of his successful ancestor's. Could possibly even ruin the brand and people would look at it as  counterfeit Cadbury.  Lawyers also don't care who your great, great, great grandfather is. You're not him. You don't own the company. Yes you own the surname but the surname alone and nothing more. You shouldn't be any more likely to get an investment than the next chocolate brand. Sure you can use the name because it's your surname but there's a strong implication here people are gonna buy it because they are fooled that it's the same company and therefore same quality formula and just why bother make another chocolate using the Cadburys name when there's already a company using Cadburys which people would rather buy from anyway? It's clearly only about money. If you have real belief in your chocolate, you don't need to rely on any associations or the name to sell it. Sure its your surname and it's a good backstory ..... if you were part of the company! Therefore theres no real appeal. If your great, great, great anscestors owned a successful bakers or distillery, would that make you any more skilled in that area? I don't think so. In fact the further the descent, THE LESS you are like them. His really just relying on the name. I don't think that's fair. This guy seriously thinks he deserves money off Cadbury just for having the same name and being related. It's about the bloody company. Not the name. The name is just well known. He accused Cadburys of playing the system but that's what his doing.
